{{Infobox person <!-- see Template:Infobox person for more fields for infobox --> | name = Peter Shirtcliffe | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|1931|07|28}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth) --> | death_place = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | occupation = | salary = | networth = }} '''George Peter Shirtcliffe''', {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]]}} (born 28 July 1931), is a New Zealand businessman. He was the chairman of [[Telecom New Zealand]], New Zealand's largest listed company, from 1990 to 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telecom-media.co.nz/releases_detail.asp?id=2312|title=Telecom Chairman to be Succeeded by Chief Executive|date=16 February 1999|accessdate=10 September 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720143203/http://www.telecom-media.co.nz/releases_detail.asp?id=2312|archivedate=20 July 2011|df=}}</ref> He was appointed a [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]] in the [[1988 Birthday Honours|1988 Queen's Birthday Honours]], for services to marketing and business management.<ref>[http://www.london-gazette.co.uk/issues/51367/supplements/33 ''London Gazette'' (supplement), No. 51367, 10 June 1988]. Retrieved 15 January 2013.</ref> He received the [[New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal]].<ref>http://www.dpmc.govt.nz/honours/overview/distinctive.html#CommemorationMedals</ref> He is also a Laureate of the New Zealand Business Hall of Fame,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesshalloffame.co.nz/2001.html|title=Fairfax New Zealand Business Hall of Fame|year=2001|accessdate=10 December 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524051439/http://businesshalloffame.co.nz/2001.html|archivedate=24 May 2010|df=}}</ref> a fellow of the [[New Zealand Institute of Chartered Accountants]] (honorary retired) and a Distinguished Fellow of the Institute of Directors.<ref>http://www.iod.org.nz/</ref> He was the founding chairman of the Enterprise Education Foundation and later a trustee of the Enterprise New Zealand Trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enzt.co.nz/~enztWeb/documents/EntMattersIssue4.pdf|title=Enterprise Matters|year=2008|accessdate=14 December 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> He was an active member of the [[Royal New Zealand Naval Volunteer Reserve]] from 1953 to 1967, reaching the rank of Lieutenant Commander.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/wellington/2712795/Tired-hungry-but-happy-on-national-service|title=Tired, hungry but happy on national service|work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]|date=3 August 2009|first=Rebecca|last=Palmer}}</ref>
==MMP== During the debate over [[electoral reform in New Zealand]] in the early 1990s, he led the [[Campaign for Better Government]] which unsuccessfully opposed the [[Mixed Member Proportional]] system. In the late 2000s, he campaigned for changes to the format of the 2011 referendum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzcpr.com/guest120.htm|title=A Political Priority|first=Peter|last=Shirtcliffe|date=20 October 2008|publisher=The New Zealand Centre for Political Research|accessdate=10 September 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090910085651/http://www.nzcpr.com/guest120.htm|archivedate=10 September 2009|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/2839243/MMP-may-be-back-for-debate|title=MMP may be back for debate|work=[[The Dominion Post (Wellington)|The Dominion Post]]|date=7 September 2009|first=Tracy|last=Watkins|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5jbFg230N?url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/2839243/MMP-may-be-back-for-debate|archivedate=7 September 2009}}</ref>
