{{short description|American business academic}}
'''Theodore Parker Smith''' was a leader at business colleges in the U.S. He ran Smith's Business College in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]].
== Early life == Smith was a Missouri native,{{cn|date=January 2018}} graduated from [[Lincoln University (Pennsylvania)]] in 1888<ref>{{Cite book|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=Usa-_VgFkrgC|page=135}}|title=Nathan B. Young and the Struggle Over Black Higher Education|last=Holland|first=Antonio Frederick|date=2006|publisher=University of Missouri Press|year=|isbn=9780826265500|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> and married Clara Alexander of Lynchburg.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=jm9TPgAACAAJ|page=99}}|title=African American Women Writers in New Jersey, 1836-2000: A Biographical Dictionary and Bibliographic Guide|last=Moses|first=Sibyl E.|date=2006|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=|isbn=9780813540191|location=|pages=99|language=en}}</ref>
== Career == An 1899 advertisement in the ''[[Richmond Planet]]'' announced that the school offered courses in “phonographic, penning, commercial, English…”,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16497113/advertisement_richmond_planet/|title=[Advertisement] Richmond Planet (Richmond, Virginia) 22 Jul 1899, page 2 - Newspapers.com|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en}}</ref> and a 1908 publication lauded Smith as “one of the pioneers” in the work of training African Americans in business principles.
By 1897, he was a professor at a business college in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16496010/freom_lynchburg_richmond_planet/|title=From Lynchburg, Richmond Planet (Richmond, Virginia) 20 Nov 1897, page 4 - Newspapers.com|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en}}</ref> He later served as president and manager of Smith's Business College in Lynchburg where he taught stenography and bookkeeping. In 1910, Smith left that position to join the faculty of the National Religious Training School (a predecessor of [[North Carolina Central University]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16496828/able_addresses_richmond_planet/|title=Able Addresses, Richmond Planet (Richmond, Virginia) 6 Aug 1910, page 5 - Newspapers.com|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en}}</ref>
By 1911 they had moved to Durham, North Carolina, where he was the Dean of the Commercial Department at the school.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16497659/|title=Clipping from The Wilmington Morning Star - Newspapers.com|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en}}</ref> Clara served as the head of the Teacher’s Department.<ref>Begin Second Year of Training School, Winston-Salem Journal (Winston-Salem, North Carolina) 12 Oct 1911, page 7, accessed January 13, 2018 at https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16497803/</ref> He taught at the North Carolina State Summer School for Negro Teachers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16497854/summer_school_at_greensboro_the_new/|title=Summer School at Greensboro, The New York Age (New York, New York) 1 Aug 1912, page 8 - Newspapers.com|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en}}</ref>
They later moved to Kansas City, Missouri and in August 1933 Smith was hit in the hip by a stray bullet shot by fleeing bank robbers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16496380/|title=Tear Gas Blinds Robbers, Two Wounded by Wild Shots|last=|first=|date=26 August 1933|work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en}}</ref> By 1934, Smith was operating a new Smith’s Business College in Kansas City, Missouri.{{cn|date=January 2018}}
== Personal life == Smith's children included Myra Lyle Smith Kearse, who in turn was the mother of [[Amalya Lyle Kearse]].<ref name=":0" />
